07122nam a22011655i 9783110252859DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20112011gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)775373227  a97831102528597 a10.1515/97831102528592doi  a(DE-B1597)123357  a(OCoLC)768572167  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPN56.L33bB56 2011 7aLIT0041302bisacsh04a800a809.93356100aBioethics and Biolaw through Literature /ced. by Daniela Carpi. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (372 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw & Literature ,x2191-8457 ;v20 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years, the well-established field of human anthropology has been put under scrutiny by the new data offered by science and technology. Scientific intervention into human life through organ transplants, euthanasia, genetic engineering, experiments connected to the genetic code and the genome, and varied other biotechnologies have placed ethical beliefs into question and created ethical dilemmas. These scientific inventions influence our views on birth and death, on the construction of the body and its technical reproducibility, and have problematized the concept of the human persona. The purpose of bioethics, the science of life, is to find new values and norms which will be valid for a multicultural society. Bioethics is, today, a well-respected topic of research that has brought together philosophers and experts to discuss the limits of science and medicine. The aim of this book is to merge the two fields of bioethics and law (or biolaw) through the literary text, by taking into consideration the transformations of the concept of persona at which we have nowadays arrived. The new meaning of the term ‘persona’ represents in fact the final point of a long-standing quest for man's sense of his own being and human dignity, and of his capacity to live in social interrelations. The volume presents a wide range of perspectives, comprising methodological approaches, legal and literary aspects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aBioethics in literature. 0aLaw and literature. 0aSelf in literature. 4aBioethik. 4aBiorecht. 4aRecht und Literatur. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aBioethics.  aBiolaw.  aLaw and Literature.1 aAdami, Valentina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aApostoli, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBattisti, Chiara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBellman, Patrizia Nerozzi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBezrucka, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryan, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarbone, Paola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarpi, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarpi, Daniela, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCheung, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDahlberg, Leif, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrakakis, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFiorato, Sidia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaakeer, Jeanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLogaldo, Mara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonti, Silvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabkin, Eric S., econtributor.4